2026-06-26 | Distinct Subsequences

	Question
Return the total number of subsequences of s1 that are equal to s2, modulo 10^9 + 7.
	Key Insight
At every character of s1, we have two choices:
		1. Skip the current character.
		2. If it matches the current character of s2,
		   use it in the subsequence.
This naturally leads to Dynamic Programming.
	State Definition
		dp[i][j]
	= Number of ways to form
		s2[0...j-1]
	using
		s1[0...i-1].
	Base Cases
•	Empty s2 can always be formed:
		dp[i][0] = 1
•	Non-empty s2 cannot be formed from empty s1:
		dp[0][j] = 0
	Transition
If characters match:
		s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]
	then
		dp[i][j]
		=
		dp[i-1][j]
		+
		dp[i-1][j-1]
	where
		dp[i-1][j]
			→ Skip current character.
		dp[i-1][j-1]
			→ Use current character.
If characters do not match:
		dp[i][j]
		=
		dp[i-1][j]
	Time Complexity
	O(n × m)
	where
		n = |s1|
		m = |s2|
	Space Complexity
	O(m)
	using space optimization.
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int distinctSubsequences(string s1, string s2) {
        const int MOD = 1000000007;
        int n = s1.size();
        int m = s2.size();
        vector<long long> dp(m + 1, 0);
        dp[0] = 1;
        for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            for(int j = m; j >= 1; j--) {
                if(s1[i - 1] == s2[j - 1]) {
                    dp[j] = (dp[j] + dp[j - 1]) % MOD;
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[m];
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		s1 = "banana"
		s2 = "ban"
	Valid subsequences:
		ban (using first a, first n)
		ban (using first a, second n)
		ban (using second a, second n)
	Output:
		3
	Key Insight
	For every character in `s1`, either ignore it or use it (only if it matches the current character of `s2`). Updating the DP array from right to left ensures that each character of `s1` is used at most once while counting all possible subsequences, giving an O(n × m) time and O(m) space solution.
